annotations.text: Human culture is as rich and diverse as it is because human intelligence is so complex and dynamic. We all have great natural capacities, but we all have them differently. There are not two types of people, academic or non academic. We all have distinctive profiles of intellectual abilities with different strengths in visual intelligences, in sound, in movement, in mathematical thinking and the rest. Academic education looks only at certain sorts of ability. Those who have it often have other abilities that are ignored: those who don't are likely to be seen as not intelligent at all. Highly able people are turned away from companies or lost in them because their education tells the wrong story. If we're serious about developing human resources, the first step is to recognize how diverse and individual those resources are.

As the technological revolution gathers pace, education and training are thought to be the answer to everything. They are, but we have to understand the question. Educating more people - and to a much higher standard - is vital. But we also have to educate them differently. The problem is that present expansion is based on a fundamental misconception: the confusion of academic ability with intelligence. For years academic ability has been conflated with intelligence, and this idea has been institutionalised into testing systems, examinations, selection procedures, teacher education and research. As a result, many highly intelligent people have passed through education feeling they aren't. Many academically able people have never discovered their other abilities.

The misconception that academic success is  <u>synonymous</u> with intelligence has been a fundamental flaw in educational systems worldwide. The ability to perform well in exams or to master a narrow set of academic skills is often mistaken for a comprehensive measure of a person's intellect. Consequently, students who may excel in practical or creative fields often feel  <u>marginalized</u> in a system that primarily rewards memorization and analytical skills of the standardized tests. This has led to an education system that can  <u>suppress</u> talent and diversity in thinking. By equating intelligence solely with academic achievements, educational institutions risk neglecting the nurturing of talents that do not necessarily fit with traditional academic metrics but are equally important. Educational reform is needed to address this  <u>unevenness</u>, promoting an inclusive approach that values all forms of intelligence. Recognizing the breadth of human capability is  <u>contradictory</u> to developing educational policies that support all students, not just those who excel academically. By doing so, we can foster a society where various forms of intelligence are recognized and valued equally.

annotations.text: Green walls have become a rising new trend in the built environments in recent years. This oxygen reaches a city dweller with a living wall if he or she is sitting on the balcony or sitting inside the home with the window open. Having a view of the vertical wall garden from the interior of the home will both reduce stress and increase the green view.
